The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Satyam posts 18% rise in net, buys two firms
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Satyam posts 18% rise in net, buys two firms
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Ramalinga Raju in Hyderabad on Monday (AFP)                                  
	Mumbai, April 21: Satyam Computer Services today reported an 18.6 per cent rise in consolidated net profit for the fourth quarter ended March 31, 2008, at Rs 466.85 crore against Rs 393.58 crore in the corresponding quarter a year ago.        
	Total income of Satyam increased 31.9 per cent to Rs 2,438.99 crore from Rs 1,849.55 crore. In 2007-08, total income rose 31.1 per cent to Rs 8,740.69 crore from Rs 6,668.36 crore in the last fiscal.         
	The companys consolidated net profit for 2007-08 rose 20.2 per cent to Rs 1,687.89 crore from Rs 1,404.74 crore a year ago.         
	Satyam also announced two acquisitions that cost close to $100 million.         
	It has agreed to acquire S amp;V Management Consultants, a Ghent, Belgium-based supply chain management consulting firm for $35.5 million in an all-cash deal.        
	In another second deal, Satyam and Caterpillar Inc, a manufacturer of construction and mining equipment, have agreed to the sale of Caterpillars market research and customer analytics operations for $60 million.         
	Satyam will now launch a business unit to provide research and analytics solutions globally. We are excited to acquire an established supply chain management firm (S amp;V Management) that is respected for its innovation, high quality, and high-end supply chain strategy services, said B. Ramalinga Raju, chairman of Satyam Computer Services.        
	On the Caterpillar deal, Raju said: We were honoured to be named one of Caterpillars few strategic partners in 2005, and this acquisition further demonstrates the trust both organisations have in each other.         
	It also accelerates development of our business transformation capabilities and further enhances our end-to-end business solutions  from strategy to BPO. It is a significant step in our march towards becoming true business transformation partners with our customer, he said.                                                                                                                                     
